    <!-- Article Content -->
    <article class="mt-20 prose dark:prose-invert max-w-4xl border-t border-hairline pt-16">
      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink font-sans mb-6">The Metrics of Body Size: BMI, BMI Prime, and Ponderal Index</h2>
      <div class="text-body text-sm md:text-base font-sans leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>
          Evaluating whether body weight falls within a healthy range is typically addressed through public health standard indexes. The most commonly used tool is the <strong>Body Mass Index (BMI)</strong>, also known as the Quetelet Index. Created by Belgian statistician Adolphe Quetelet in the 19th century, BMI provides a quick estimate of a person's total body mass relative to height.
        </p>
        <p>
          The basic formula calculates weight in kilograms divided by the square of height in meters ($kg / m^2$):
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 font-sans text-sm">
          <li><strong>Metric Formula:</strong> BMI = Weight (kg) / Height (m)&sup2;</li>
          <li><strong>Imperial Formula:</strong> BMI = (Weight (lbs) &times; 703) / Height (in)&sup2;</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">Understanding BMI Prime and Ponderal Index</h3>
        <p>
          While standard BMI is a quick baseline, other math modifications offer more detail:
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>BMI Prime</strong> is a simple ratio of your actual BMI to the upper limit of the normal weight BMI range (defined globally as 25).
          <br />
          <strong class="block my-2 text-center text-ink font-mono text-xs">BMI Prime = Actual BMI / 25</strong>
          A value of 1.0 represents the exact threshold between normal weight and overweight. Values below 0.74 represent underweight ranges, and values above 1.00 represent overweight or obese weight classifications. This makes relative comparisons easier to analyze.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Ponderal Index (PI)</strong>, also known as the Rohrer Index, is calculated by dividing weight by height cubed:
          <br />
          <strong class="block my-2 text-center text-ink font-mono text-xs">Ponderal Index = Weight (kg) / Height (m)&sup3;</strong>
          Because standard BMI divides by height squared, it assumes a two-dimensional body shape. Humans are three-dimensional, meaning that taller individuals tend to register a higher standard BMI despite having identical relative body compositions. Ponderal Index cubes height to account for three-dimensional body mass volume, which yields more consistent comparisons for exceptionally tall or short individuals.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">Health Status Classifications and Limitations</h3>
        <p>
          The clinical zones established by the World Health Organization (WHO) categorize body weight as follows:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 font-sans text-sm">
          <li><strong>Underweight:</strong> BMI less than 18.5.</li>
          <li><strong>Normal Range:</strong> BMI between 18.5 and 24.9.</li>
          <li><strong>Overweight:</strong> BMI between 25.0 and 29.9.</li>
          <li><strong>Obesity Class I:</strong> BMI between 30.0 and 34.9.</li>
          <li><strong>Obesity Class II:</strong> BMI between 35.0 and 39.9.</li>
          <li><strong>Obesity Class III:</strong> BMI equal to or greater than 40.0.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          <strong>Limitations of BMI:</strong> Because the formulas only account for total weight and height, BMI cannot distinguish weight from muscle mass versus body fat. A muscular athlete or weightlifter may have a high BMI that indicates they are overweight, despite having a low body fat percentage. Always pair BMI with other body composition analysis methods, such as circumference measurements, calipers, or bioelectrical impedance, to get a complete picture of your health.
        </p>
      
<h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">The Body Composition Blindspot of BMI</h3>
        <p>
          While the Body Mass Index (BMI) is a valuable epidemiological tool for categorizing large populations, it has a significant blindspot: it cannot distinguish between skeletal muscle mass and adipose fat tissue. Because muscle tissue is roughly 18% denser than fat tissue, a highly muscular individual, weightlifter, or professional athlete can have a high body weight relative to their height. As a result, the standard formulas will classify them as "overweight" or "obese," even if they have an extremely low body fat percentage and zero cardiovascular risk. Consequently, BMI should not be used as the sole indicator of health for active individuals.
        </p>
        <p>
          Furthermore, BMI does not account for the distribution of body fat. Visceral fat (fat stored around internal organs in the abdominal area) carries a much higher risk of metabolic syndrome, type 2 diabetes, and heart disease than subcutaneous fat (fat stored directly under the skin, such as in the hips or thighs). A person can have a "normal" BMI score of 22 but still carry dangerous levels of visceral abdominal fat—a clinical condition colloquially known as "skinny fat" or metabolically obese normal weight.
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">Utilizing Waist-to-Height Ratio (WHtR) as an Alternative</h3>
        <p>
          To offset the limitations of standard BMI, clinicians frequently pair height and weight numbers with abdominal measurements, such as the Waist-to-Height Ratio (WHtR) or waist circumference. The general rule of thumb for WHtR is to keep your waist circumference below half of your height (a ratio of 0.50 or less). This measurement focuses specifically on central abdominal fat and serves as a highly reliable predictor of obesity-related health risks, regardless of muscle mass variations.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>

    <!-- FAQ Section -->
    
    <!-- FAQ Section -->
    <section class="max-w-4xl pt-16 mt-20 border-t border-hairline" aria-label="Frequently Asked Questions">
      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink font-sans mb-8 text-pretty">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <details class="bg-canvas ring-1 ring-inset ring-hairline rounded-xl overflow-hidden shadow-lvl2 group">
